    }, {
      "text": "You\u0027ve encountered a classic \"inside-out\" normal problem. This is an extremely common issue when setting up collisions for the first time.\n\nThe symptom you describe—the car being pushed *into* the wall instead of *away* from it—happens for one simple reason: **the wall\u0027s normal vector is pointing in the wrong direction.**\n\n### The Problem: The Direction of the Normal\n\nIn `checkBarrierCollisions`, you calculate the normal like this:\n\n```nim\n// 1. Calculate the normal of the wall we hit\nlet wallNormal \u003d norm(cross(v1 - v0, v2 - v0))\n```\n\nThis calculation depends on the **winding order** of the vertices (`v0`, `v1`, `v2`) in your barrier model.\n*   If the vertices are ordered counter-clockwise (CCW) from the camera\u0027s point of view, the cross product will point \"out\" of the face (correctly).\n*   If they are ordered clockwise (CW), the cross product will point \"into\" the face (incorrectly).\n\nYour barrier\u0027s normals are almost certainly pointing inwards, towards the track, instead of outwards, away from the track. When the car hits the wall, you get this inward-pointing normal and multiply it by the push-out amount, which sucks the car further into the wall.\n\n### Solution 1: The \"Dot Product\" Fix (Recommended)\n\nThis is the most robust solution because it doesn\u0027t require you to re-model anything. We can determine the correct direction of the normal at runtime by comparing it to the direction of the ray that hit it.\n\nA normal should always point *away* from the surface it represents. This means it should generally point *opposite* to the direction of the object hitting it. The dot product is perfect for this.\n\n**Modify `checkBarrierCollisions`:**\n\n```nim\n# in proc checkBarrierCollisions\n\n# ... (inside the loops, right after a collision is detected) ...\nlet dist \u003d rayTriangleIntersectDist(worldOrigin, rayDir, v0, v1, v2, collisionRayLength)\n\nif dist \u003e\u003d 0:\n  # --- COLLISION DETECTED ---\n  # 1. Calculate the raw normal of the wall we hit\n  var wallNormal \u003d norm(cross(v1 - v0, v2 - v0))\n\n  # --- THIS IS THE CRUCIAL FIX ---\n  # The normal should oppose the ray that hit it.\n  # If the dot product is positive, it means the normal is pointing in a similar\n  # direction as the ray, so it\u0027s pointing \"inward\". We need to flip it.\n  if dot(wallNormal, rayDir) \u003e 0:\n    wallNormal *\u003d -1.0\n  # --- END FIX ---\n\n  # 2. Calculate how much we need to push the car out\n  let penetrationDepth \u003d collisionRayLength - dist\n  result.pushOut +\u003d wallNormal * penetrationDepth\n  result.collided \u003d true\n\n  # ... (rest of the velocity response logic) ...\n```\n\n**How it works:**\n*   `rayDir` is the direction from the car towards the wall.\n*   `wallNormal` is the direction pointing out from the wall\u0027s surface.\n*   `dot(wallNormal, rayDir)` will be:\n    *   **Negative (\u003c 0):** The vectors are pointing in opposite directions. The normal is pointing correctly *away* from the wall and towards the car. We do nothing.\n    *   **Positive (\u003e 0):** The vectors are pointing in similar directions. This means the normal is pointing *into* the wall, in the same general direction as the ray. **This is the incorrect \"inside-out\" normal.** We fix it by multiplying it by `-1.0` to flip its direction.\n\nThis one `if` statement will guarantee that your `wallNormal` is always pointing away from the barrier and towards the car, resulting in a correct \"push-out\" response.\n\n### Solution 2: Fix the Model in Blender (Good Practice)\n\nWhile the code fix is effective, it\u0027s also good practice to ensure your models have correct normals from the start.\n\n1.  Open your `track_barrier.ply` model in Blender.\n2.  Go into **Edit Mode** (Tab key).\n3.  Select all faces (`A` key).\n4.  Go to the **Mesh** menu at the top, then **Normals** -\u003e **Recalculate Outside** (or press `Shift + N`).\n5.  You can visualize the normals by enabling the \"Face Orientation\" overlay. Go to the \"Overlays\" popover in the top-right of the 3D viewport and check the box for \"Face Orientation\". Correctly facing-outward faces will be blue; inward faces will be red. Your barriers should be blue on the side the car will hit.\n6.  Re-export your `.ply` file.\n\nDoing this will fix the root cause. However, the dot-product check in the code is still a good idea as a safety measure to make your collision system robust against any modeling errors.\n\n**I highly recommend implementing the code fix.** It\u0027s a standard, reliable technique for raycast-based collision detection.",
